DURBAN - How do astronauts go to the toilet in space? How many engineers does it take to build a space shuttle? Where does ‘space water’ come from? These were questions raised by scores of young math and science enthusiasts, who sat at the edge of their seats at the Durban Natural Science Museum on Thursday, taking in the space adventures of former NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) astronaut, Dr Donald Thomas. Thomas, from Cleveland, USA, has been on a space expedition four times between 1994 and 1997 and has orbited earth over 600 times. Thomas, now retired, is on a new mission: to inspire youth who he believes will become the next generation of space explorers. WATCH: It takes 8.5 minutes to reach space from earth  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
